description: table +‎ -ate; compare Late Latin tabulātus (“having a floor; floored”), perfect passive participle of tabulō (“to fit with planks”) + -ātus (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *-eh₂tos (suffix forming adjectives from nouns indicating the possession of a thing or a quality). Tabulō is derived from tabula (“board, plank”), of uncertain origin, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *teh₂- (a variant of *steh₂- (“to stand”)) + *-dʰlom (a variant of *-trom (suffix forming nouns denoting tools or instruments)).

verbs.description: tabulate (third-person singular simple present tabulates, present participle tabulating, simple past and past participle tabulated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To arrange in tabular form; to arrange into a table.
(transitive) To set out as a list; to enumerate, to list.
examples: Synonyms: recite; see also Thesaurus:tick off

entries.meaning: (transitive, Scotland, obsolete) To enter into an official register or roll.
(transitive) To shape with a flat surface.

description: Tabulata (“extinct order of corals”)  +‎ -ate. Tabulata is derived from Latin tabulāta, from tabulātum (“flooring, storey”), from tabula (“board, plank”) + -tum (from -tus, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *-tus (“suffix forming action nouns from verb roots”)). See further at etymology 1. The order is so named because the corals are characterized by having tabulae.

entries.meaning: (paleontology) Describing a member of an extinct order of corals, the Tabulata: having tabulae (well-developed horizontal internal partitions within each cell).
(paleontology) A member of the order Tabulata.
